:::summary
The French Revolution (1789–1799) was the violent upheaval that toppled the French monarchy, executed thousands in the Reign of Terror, and ultimately gave rise to Napoleon Bonaparte — a decade that transformed Europe and posed the most urgent political and philosophical questions about liberty, order, and the nature of government. Unlike the American founding, which was rooted in Christian natural law and constitutional prudence, the French Revolution was driven by a secular, rationalist ideology that produced unprecedented bloodshed and ultimately delivered tyranny in place of freedom.
:::

